"body":"In 1887 she patented a dam and reservoir system using a series of ascending dams, each braced by the water against the one below. Congress adopted that mechanism when it approved the Hoover Dam project in 1928."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Walnut Queen of Whittier within five years","body":"Widowed at 39 with four daughters and a near-bankrupt ranch, she taught herself scientific agriculture by reading journals. Within five years she planted 150 acres of walnuts and became the largest commercial walnut grower in the United States."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"I had the courage of ignorance and determination","body":"Her husband Charles Lyman Strong had committed suicide after business failures, leaving her with four daughters and an unprofitable ranch near Whittier. Of her self-taught success she later said: 'I had the courage of ignorance and plenty of determination to back it up.'"},{"number":4,"category":"social_reform","header":"Traveled with Susan B. Anthony for women's suffrage","body":"She traveled with Susan B. Anthony promoting women's suffrage, hosting Anthony at her Rancho del Fuerte in 1895. She was the first woman member of the Los Angeles Chamber of Commerce and the first woman delegate to the U.S. Chamber of Commerce convention in 1918."},{"number":5,"category":"legacy","header":"It was thought of by a woman","body":"Appearing before Congress in 1918 to urge a series of Colorado River dams, she said: 'It was thought of by a woman.' Congress eventually built the Hoover Dam (1935) and the All-American Canal (1942) — both reflecting her ideas."}],"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"I01123","date_year":1863,"location_state":"Nevada","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1883,"children_ids":[],"notes":"Met in Nevada 1863, four years after the Comstock Lode discovery."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Harriet Williams Russell Strong","first_name":"Harriet","last_name":"Strong","maiden_name":"Russell","middle_name":"Williams","married_names":["Strong"],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1779242567/harrietlymanstrong_d2kyxn.jpg"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"harriet-strong-1844"},"I01123":{"id":"I01123","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"bio":{"first_name":"Charles","middle_name":"Lyman","last_name":"Strong","married_names":[],"gender":"male","display_name":"Charles Lyman Strong","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1779242693/charleslymanstrong_sctvde.png"},"birth":{"year":1826,"state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1883,"month":2,"day":9,"city":"Ophir","county":"Placer","state":"California","country":"United States","cause":"Suicide following business failures"},"burial":{},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":true,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_name":"David Ellsworth Strong","mother_name":"Harriet Fay Strong"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD1328","date_year":1863,"location_state":"Nevada","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_self","end_year":1883,"children_ids":[],"notes":"Met Hattie in Nevada 1863 (four years after Comstock Lode discovery brought the Russell family to Carson City). She was 19; he was 37."}],"education":[],"career":[{"role":"Mining Engineer + Superintendent","organization":"Gould & Curry Mine","location":"Virginia City, Nevada","notes":"Superintendent during the height of Comstock Lode silver mining boom; forced to resign following mental breakdown."}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["mining","suicide_death"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"death","header":"Suicide at Ophir 1883 left widow with four","body":"After a series of business failures following his forced resignation from the Gould & Curry superintendency, Charles took his own life at Ophir CA on 9 February 1883 at age 56-57. His widow Hattie inherited the failing properties and would transform them into the Ranchito del Fuerte agricultural empire that made her one of America's first famous female inventors and conservationists."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Comstock boom superintendent who lost his grip","body":"As superintendent of the Gould & Curry mine in Virginia City Nevada — one of the richest silver mines of the Comstock Lode era — he carried enormous financial and operational pressure. The strain triggered a mental breakdown that forced his resignation; he moved his family to Oakland to focus on rest, farming, and travel."},{"number":3,"category":"marriage","header":"Met Hattie in Nevada four years after Comstock","body":"The 1859 Comstock Lode silver discovery had lured the Russell family from Buffalo to Carson City Nevada by 1861. There the 37-year-old mining engineer met 19-year-old Hattie Russell, granddaughter of Col. Samuel Andrew Russell; they married in 1863."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"label":"Find A Grave - Charles Lyman Strong"},{"label":"WikiTree Strong-4850 / Strong (Charles Lyman)"},{"label":"Mary Baker Eddy Library biographical research on Harriet Williams Russell Strong"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"charles-strong-1826"},"H00844":{"id":"H00844","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":6,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1759,"month":12,"day":30,"city":"Windsor","county":"Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00358","mother_id":"X00411"},"tags":["revolutionary_war","postmaster","yale_graduate","politician","patriot","judge"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","entry":"844"},{"label":"Franklin B. Dexter, Biographical Sketches of the Graduates of Yale College Vol. IV (1907) pp. 163-164"},{"label":"Henry Reed Stiles + Sherman W Adams, Families of Ancient Wethersfield Vol. II"},{"label":"SAR Patriot #P-283245 + DAR #A098524"},{"label":"Find A Grave - Forest Lawn Cemetery Buffalo"}],"death":{"year":1834,"month":7,"day":2,"city":"Buffalo","county":"Erie","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"political_offices":[{"title":"Member","jurisdiction":"New York State Assembly","dates":"1806, 1807, 1816"},{"title":"Judge","jurisdiction":"Niagara County NY","dates":"1817-1834"},{"title":"Delegate","jurisdiction":"New York Constitutional Convention","dates":"1821"},{"title":"Presidential Elector","jurisdiction":"New York","dates":"1824"},{"title":"Postmaster","jurisdiction":"Buffalo NY","dates":"1831-1834"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00413","children_ids":["HD1323"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1783,"marriage_year":1783},{"spouse_id":"X00414","children_ids":["HD1324","HD1325","HD1326","HD1327","HD6128"],"marriage_number":2,"date_year":1790,"marriage_year":1790},{"spouse_id":"X00415","children_ids":[],"marriage_number":3,"date_year":1809,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1819,"location_state":"New York","location_country":"United States","marriage_year":1809}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":3,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Col. Samuel Andrews Russell","first_name":"Samuel","last_name":"Russell","title":"Colonel","middle_name":"Andrews","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"alumnus"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"burial":{"plot_notes":"Forest Lawn Cemetery, Buffalo NY"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Postmaster of Buffalo, appointed April 1831","body":"Appointed Postmaster of Buffalo NY in April 1831 by President Andrew Jackson; held the office until his death on 2 July 1834. The Yale biographical sketch summarized: 'loved, esteemed, and respected by all who knew him.'"},{"number":2,"category":"politics","header":"NY Constitutional Convention 1821, Elector 1824","body":"Served as a delegate to the New York State Constitutional Convention of 1821 — which revised the state constitution to broaden suffrage and reorganize the judiciary. Selected as a Presidential Elector for New York in the 1824 election."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"Niagara County Judge from April 1817","body":"First appointed Judge in Niagara County NY in April 1817 — shortly after his removal from New York City to Buffalo. Held judicial office in western New York's frontier period when Niagara County still encompassed much of the territory later subdivided into Erie and other counties."},{"number":4,"category":"marriage","header":"Married two of the three Woodward sisters","body":"After his first wife Lucy Munson died at 29 in 1785 leaving a daughter, he married Sarah Woodward of New Haven in November 1790. She died suddenly in New York August 1807; around 1809 he then married her sister Susan Woodward, who died September 1819 in her 63rd year."},{"number":5,"category":"military","header":"Revolutionary War private under Capt. Peter Vail","body":"Served as a private in the Connecticut militia under Captain Peter Vail and Colonel Canfield during the Revolutionary War. SAR Patriot #P-283245 + DAR #A098524. His Yale studies followed wartime service and graduation around 1779 — he remained at Yale as graduate student and Butler until May 1783."}],"slug":"samuel-russell-1759"},"X00414":{"id":"X00414","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":[],"sources":[],"death":{"year":1807,"month":8,"day":8,"city":"New York","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"gender":"female","parents":{},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"H00844","date_year":1790,"children_ids":["HD1324","HD1325","HD1326","HD1327","HD6128"],"marriage_year":1790}],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"birth":{"year":1763,"country":"United States"},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Sarah Woodward","first_name":"Sarah","maiden_name":"Woodward","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"sarah-woodward-1763"},"H00358":{"id":"H00358","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":5,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1725,"month":7,"day":23,"city":"Middletown","state":"Connecticut"},"parents":{"father_id":"I00144","mother_id":"H00118"},"tags":["minister","yale_graduate"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 358"}],"death":{"year":1775,"month":4,"day":20,"city":"Windsor","state":"Connecticut"},"church_roles":[{"role":"Pastor","location":"First Church of Windsor","dates":"1751-1775 (ordained Jul 24, 1754)"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00411","children_ids":["H00843","H00844"